<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Introduction -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<h2>INTRODUCTION </h2>
<P>
<FONT >The United States leads the world in the discovery
of the new drugs, biologics and medical devices that offer the
promise of longer and healthier lives for our citizens.  But the
process of actually developing these products and getting them
approved for marketing has become increasingly lengthy, expensive
and complex.  The past several decades have seen breathtaking
scientific breakthroughs in areas such as biotechnology and computing.
 But these breakthroughs have yet to be translated in a significant
way into new medical products that benefit patients.  Regulatory
demands and delays are not the only reasons for this stagnation,
but they are significant factors.  America's regulatory procedures
are among the slowest and most expensive in the developed world,
and it is now common for U.S. companies to conduct product testing
and development abroad and for new drugs and devices to be available
first in other countries.  Consider the following:</FONT>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><FONT >The time required to bring a new drug to
market in the United States, from chemical synthesis to marketing,
has increased steadily, from slightly more than six years in the
mid-1960s to almost 15 years currently<sup><a href="foot.html">1</a></sup>.</FONT>
<LI><FONT >The percentage of drugs first available
in the United States is low.  Seventy-three percent of drugs approved
by the FDA during 1987-93 had already been approved elsewhere.
 In the area of anticancer agents, for example, the United States
once led the world and now lags behind other nations.  During
the 1960s, cancer patients in the United States had more anticancer
agents available to them than did patients in Great Britain, Germany,
France or Japan.  Now, in contrast, patients in the United States
have fewer anticancer agents available than those in any of these
countries.<sup><a href="foot.html">2</a></sup></FONT>
<LI><FONT >In the medical device area, a product that
takes four years to bring to market in Europe frequently requires
six years in the United States<sup><a href="foot.html">3</a></sup>.  As a result, medical device manufacturers
in large numbers are first introducing their products offshore,
and American patients increasingly are receiving therapies that
are a generation or more behind those available in Europe.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT > </FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Reversing these trends will require a fundamental
change in the framework used to bring new medical products to
the market.  Many studies have been performed and expert groups
convened with the goal of reforming drug and device oversight.
 But, they have failed to yield significant improvement in the
only meaningful bottom line:  total development times and product
availability.  Those reforms that have been adopted have been
too marginal to have an appreciable overall impact on improving
the system.  (Recent evidence may suggest that marketing approvals
recently have become slightly more expeditious, but no impact
has been seen on the overall time and cost of development).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Therefore, we propose a revised framework for
approving drugs and medical devices that does not alter the basic
objectives underlying the existing system:  that medical products
are evaluated by qualified experts on the basis of adequate data;
that they meet appropriate standards, defined in terms of the
relationship between benefits and risks; and, that they perform
as claimed on the label.  The regulatory process should be designed
to block dangerous or ineffective products; but, it should also
speed salubrious ones to the clinic.  The existing review and
approval procedures have achieved some success at ensuring that
products admitted to the market are reasonably safe and effective.
 But this benefit has been achieved at great direct and indirect
cost to patients, industry and government, with the introduction
of many promising new therapies delayed or prevented entirely.
 Much of this cost is unnecessary:  safety and effectiveness do
not have to be sacrificed by the introduction of greater regulatory
efficiency.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >A NEW INSTITUTIONAL FRAMEWORK</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has
a statutory mandate to assure that new drugs and devices are safe
and effective.  This mandate is combined with a &quot;monopoly&quot;
on new product approvals.  It is the monopoly part of this framework
that is the principal source of current deficiencies in drug and
device oversight, because there is no institutional check on the
regulatory creep that inexorably has added time, costs, and unpredictability
to the review process.  In fact, the FDA has raised the regulatory
burden on product sponsors by continually introducing new requirements
and policies without regard for their negative impact on the delivery
of new and innovative therapies to patients.  As long as the only
route to the market is through the FDA, the adverse trends in
product availability and development times are likely to continue.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Improving the balance of incentives, therefore,
requires opening the product certification process to competitive
forces.  If one extreme of the &quot;institutional spectrum&quot;
is represented by the current FDA monopoly, the other pole is
represented by complete laissez faire, under which decisions to
market drugs and devices would be made by manufacturers without
government regulatory oversight.  In theory, manufacturers would
still be constrained, by the desire to maintain the reputation
of their products and avoid litigation.  But our proposal rejects
this alternative.  Although a laissez-faire system may have some
merits, particularly for established firms with reputations to
protect, it may also provide firms with an incentive to take unwarranted
risks.  Moreover, most American consumers want a required independent
review to ensure safety and effectiveness.  For these and other
reasons, laissez faire is not a viable option for bringing new
medical products to the market in the United States.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The plan proposal, described here, maintains
existing or equivalent government standards and oversight, as
well as the FDA stamp of approval, signifying that benefits and
risks have been evaluated and balanced appropriately.  At the
same time, the proposal relies on nongovernmental bodies for review
and certification.  In this model, <I>the FDA is primarily a certifier
of certifiers, rather than a certifier of products.</I>  The element
of competition among the nongovernmental certifying bodies for
sponsors' business is an important element of the proposal.  By
providing product sponsors with choice among certifying bodies,
but retaining high product standards, the system institutes a
review process that is responsive to the needs of patients and
product development.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>

<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
