<DOCNO>WT15-B29-5</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA039-000745-B040-198</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.empower.org:80/pff/mip/1-app.html 204.71.237.79 19970210100026 text/html 6052
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 10-Feb-97 10:01:12 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:36:14 GMT
Content-length: 5867
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<CENTER><B><FONT >Appendix: The Private Monopoly Laboratory
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >Suppose that the monopoly laboratory has an
oversight committee. For purposes of clarity, naively assume that
the committee members are interested in maximizing consumer welfare,
and, therefore, political variables are ruled out. The monopolist
is assumed to be a standard profit-maximizer producing certifications
at a price, P. Price is a function of the number of new drugs
certified, ND, and safety, s, of the drugs. Thus, P=p(ND,s). Total
cost is a function of safety and the number of new drugs certified,
and increases with respect to safety. Thus, C=c(ND,s). <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The oversight committee is interested in maximizing
consumer welfare, W, and, therefore, would like the area under
the demand curve and above production costs to be maximized, i.e.,
it would like the monopoly to maximize:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (1) <IMG SRC="IMG00004.GIF">.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The first-order conditions are:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (2) <IMG SRC="IMG00005.GIF"><IMG SRC="IMG00006.GIF"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT >and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (3) <IMG SRC="IMG00007.GIF"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT >where subscripts denote partial derivatives.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The monopolist, however, is interested in maximizing
profits and therefore attempts to maximize:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (4) <IMG SRC="IMG00008.GIF"><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Its first-order conditions are:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (5) <IMG SRC="IMG00009.GIF"> and<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (6) <IMG SRC="IMG00010.GIF"><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >From (3) the oversight committee is concerned
with the impact of increased safety on all consumers (from the
integral), while from (6) the monopolist is concerned with the
impact of increased safety on the marginal consumer. Furthermore,
when <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (7) <IMG SRC="IMG00011.GIF"></FONT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="IMG00012.GIF">
<P>
<FONT >the monopolist undersupplies safety from the
oversight committee's point of view. The committee then arguably
orders the monopoly to increase the safety of its certified drugs
at the cost of reduced monopoly profits. It is important to note,
however, that it may not be possible for the oversight committee
to discern the consumer-maximizing output decision. The monopoly
may exaggerate the impact of increased safety on price, P<SUB>s</SUB>,
to the extent that the inequality in (7) becomes an equality.
In this case the oversight committee believes that the appropriate
level of safety is being provided, when in reality the level of
safety is not as high as desired. Even when the committee has
oversight on the level of profits realized, the monopoly may engage
in X-inefficiency, and thus still provide lower than desired levels
of safety.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Dorfman and Steiner (1954) modeled a monopolist
whose product demand is a function of price and advertising. Consider
this approach but, instead, focus on safety rather than advertising.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Thus, the monopolist maximizes:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (8) <IMG SRC="IMG00013.GIF"><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >where the cost function is now additive in
new drugs and safety and, as before, ND=N(p,s). Maximizing with
respect to p and s, the first-order conditions are:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (9) <IMG SRC="IMG00014.GIF"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT >and</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (10) <IMG SRC="IMG00015.GIF"><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >where, again, subscripts denote partial derivatives.
Denoting E<SUB>p</SUB> = -ND<SUB>p</SUB>[p/ND] as the elasticity
of demand with respect to price and E<SUB>s </SUB>= -ND<SUB>s</SUB>[s/ND]
as the elasticity of demand with respect to drug safety, then,
as Dorfman and Steiner showed, (9) and (10) can be rearranged
as<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > (11) <IMG SRC="IMG00016.GIF"><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This is a version of the Dorfman-Steiner condition.
For a given E<SUB>s,</SUB> the greater the elasticity of demand
with respect to price, E<SUB>p</SUB>, the smaller the safety to
sales of new drugs ratio. Given that the demand for new drugs
is highly inelastic with respect to price, which in the case of
life-threatening diseases may the case, safety relative to total
sales of new drugs will be high, other thing equal.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Nonetheless, given the simplistic nature of
this analysis, the oversight committee may get less safety than
the amount desired. This is the case when the marginal valuation
of safety to the average consumer is greater than that of the
marginal consumer. In an attempt to maximize profits the monopolist
undersupplies safety, according to the oversight committee. Also,
when the price elasticity of demand for new drugs is high relative
to the safety elasticity of demand, the level of safe certifications
relative to total sales of new drugs is low. And, as stressed
above, by exaggerating the impact of safety on price, the monopoly
can still maximize profits by undersupplying certification of
safe new drugs, and even if the committee regulates its profits,
the monopoly may still undersupply safety by engaging in X-inefficiency.
The point is simply that even with a benign oversight committee
bent on maximizing consumer welfare, regulation of the monopoly
laboratory easily becomes a quagmire. And, undoubtedly, the more
realistic the model is made, the deeper the quagmire.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>

<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
