</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: New Regulation -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<P>

<h3>THE PROPOSED NEW SYSTEM:  REGULATION
OF DRUGS AND BIOLOGICS</h3>
<BR>
<FONT >The goal of the plan is to speed the delivery
of safe and effective products to patients who require them. 
To achieve that, changes in current federal regulation are proposed
that will facilitate early clinical research; increase the efficiency
of drug development and the constructiveness of its regulatory
oversight; and reduce the overall time and cost required for a
new drug to reach the market.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > </FONT>
<P>
<FONT >While improving the process for developing,
reviewing, and approving new drugs and biologics, this proposal
maintains existing safety and effectiveness standards by preserving
the legal requirements for pre-market demonstration of safety
and effectiveness.  Preserved as well are FDA's enforcement powers
and the agency's final sign-off authority to approve product marketing.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The salient aspects of this proposal are the
transfer of much of the responsibility for day- to-day IND oversight
and NDA review to non-governmental experts; support of the review
mechanism (DCBs) by user fees (via contractual arrangements between
sponsors and DCBs); and competition among the non-governmental
entities that will oversee the IND process and perform reviews.
 No single component of this proposal is completely new, but the
integration of these various elements into a drug oversight and
review system is accomplished in a novel way that is both logically
sound and empirically validated.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Our plan proposes changing the system of regulatory
oversight of drug development by transferring the primary oversight
responsibility (but not the final approval step) from FDA to non-governmental
entities, Drug Certification Bodies (DCBs),that are staffed by
the experts that the law requires to make judgments on effectiveness
and safety.  This transformation of the IND oversight and NDA
review process for  individual products in development will be
more comprehensive than other, similar proposals that would, for
example, delegate piecemeal various FDA functions such as review
of NDA filings.  Competition among the DCBs to provide regulatory
oversight services, combined with safeguards against conflicts
of interest and overeagerness to approve products, will create
a more efficient drug development process and promote innovation.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >The Drug Certification Bodies (DCBs)</b>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >DCBs will be certified by FDA to ensure they
have the technical, scientific, and managerial expertise necessary
to oversee and review particular specialties or categories of
products.  The DCBs' own imperatives to compete for clients, avoid
tort liability, and retain FDA certification are the fundamental
triad that will provide the impetus for high standards.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The corporate structure, geographic location,
and number of DCBs will be determined by market forces, as will
how many DCBs emerge and survive.  DCBs may choose, for example,
to be for-profit or non-profit; to be physically located in existing
centers of medical research or near centers of the pharmaceutical
or biotechnology industry; and to specialize in particular therapeutic
areas or drug types, or be  broadly qualified for a wide range.
 The regulatory process for obtaining licensure as a DCB could
be modeled on other complex health-related licensing procedures
such as the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations
(JCAHO).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >FDA will certify the DCBs to oversee most of
the drug development process (i.e., to evaluate and issue INDs),
oversee drugs in development, and review NDA applications.<sup><a href="foot.html">3</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >At the sponsor's option, the DCB may offer
advice on what is appropriate or required in a development program
to obtain NDA approval, but ultimate approval cannot (and should
not) be guaranteed. Nor should this be part of the contract. In
the end, the results of the physico-chemical, pre-clinical, and
clinical studies will provide evidence of safety and efficacy
-- and, therefore, an indication of likely approval. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Initially, DCBs will likely recruit from FDA,
industry, and contract research organizations (CROs) the scientific,
medical, and regulatory experts required for judgments on safety
and effectiveness. Experts may be needed in fields such as pharmaceutical
toxicology, pharmaceutical formulations, biopharmaceutics, drug
study design and analysis, clinical monitoring of therapeutics
and quality assurance, chemistry, and manufacturing.<B> </B> Because
these are specialized technical undertakings, the DCB will need
a broad range of scientific, medical, regulatory, and management
expertise. For this reason alone, qualifying for and retaining
FDA certification will be challenging.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >The Sponsor's Relationship with a DCB</b>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The product sponsor (usually a company) will
select a DCB from those certified for the respective product class
-- categories might include, for example, anti-hypertensive drugs,
psychotropic drugs, or vaccines.  Important factors in that choice
will include the perceived ability of the DCB to oversee a suitable
NDA program and the likelihood of a successful DCB review and
eventual FDA approval for its particular product.  Other factors
influencing the choice might include the DCB's geographic location;
reputation for service; experience with studies of comparable
size and complexity; and, fees.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Different sponsor companies will require widely
different degrees of interaction and service from DCBs, as happens
now with sponsor-FDA interactions.  Sponsor-DCB contracts will
reflect these differing needs.  The level of service required
will depend on factors such as the size and previous experience
of the sponsor (both generally and for the particular class of
drug); the intrinsic novelty of the product; the presence of difficult
issues of purity, potency, stability, or toxicity; and the size
and complexity of the clinical program.  Other issues will sometimes
be prominent; for example, in the case of important public health
products such as influenza vaccine, there could be a compelling
need for extremely rapid testing and approval. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The needs of the sponsor companies will determine
how many DCBs can ultimately be sustained by the U.S. drug development
process, and what their special features and location will be.
 <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Role of DCB in IND Oversight and NDA Review</B>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Because the DCB will have primary supervision
over the IND, the IND submission will be made to the DCB, not
to FDA.  However, FDA will maintain its role in the national surveillance
of clinical safety of investigational drugs, as part of its responsibility
for all drug safety surveillance, as described below.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The contact between the sponsor and the DCB
will normally begin during preclinical development, well before
the expected start of clinical trials, just as sponsor-FDA interaction
often does now.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The DCB will advise on and evaluate the IND
filing and issue the IND when it is satisfied that the risk/benefit
considerations are appropriate for the commencement of  clinical
trials.  Following the granting of the IND and the IRB's (independent)
approval, the sponsor will be able to initiate the study, as at
present.  The DCB's close involvement with the sponsor will encourage
the identification and solution of problems during the pre-submission
period.  Little or no additional time -- the current 30-day waiting
period, for example -- should be needed to obtain IND approval.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The DCB will oversee the testing of the new
drug throughout its clinical research phases, concentrating on
issues of safety and efficacy.  The DCB will ensure that the sponsor
is in compliance with the currently applicable regulatory standards
(including GLPs, GCPs, and GMPs). The DCB will be responsible
for auditing the sponsor to ensure that standards have been met
in all areas and for certifying this compliance.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Once the sponsor and DCB have agreed that the
accumulated data on a product fulfill the legal requirement for
safety and efficacy, the sponsor will submit its formal New Drug
Application (NDA) to the DCB.  The DCB will be responsible for
certifying, through its regular site visits and audits of the
sponsor, that the original data are accurately recorded, analyzed,
and reported; that the data are suitably archived for future audits
if necessary; and, that the summary analyses and reports accurately
reflect the data.  The criteria for approval of the NDA will remain,
as they are now, safety and efficacy, as judged by experts (in
this case, the DCB's experts), according to the law.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Because of the DCB's continuous involvement
as the data supporting the NDA are accumulated -- a process that
has in past reform proposals been referred to as a &quot;developing&quot;
or &quot;self-reviewing&quot; NDA -- the evaluation and review
of a straightforward NDA will normally be completed rapidly after
its submission.  Also, because the DCB's report, like the NDA
itself, may be written as the NDA data are emerging, even difficult
issues to be addressed in the report -- such as marginal efficacy;
low therapeutic index; or problems with safety, stability, or
manufacturing -- will often have been identified and solved by
the DCB in the course of the IND.  Thus, a DCB's favorable recommendation
may often be issued with only a minimal additional &quot;NDA review
period.&quot;  Thus, the system will encourage a high level of
problem-solving, as the market learns to favor those DCBs that
offer competence, predictability, and a reputation for high standards.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The DCB's recommendation to the FDA for approval
of the NDA will summarize the evidence supporting a positive recommendation,
similar to (but with more detail than) the current Summary Basis
of Approval (SBA).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Role of the FDA in IND Oversight and NDA
Evaluation</B>
</FONT><P>
<FONT >FDA will be responsible for certifying DCBs
and for overarching safety concerns.  The agency will not be involved
in individual IND programs unless there is a specific safety issue
that cannot be handled through the normal oversight of the sponsor
by a competent DCB.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >On safety matters, the DCB will oversee the
sponsor, but FDA will retain its responsibilities for national
oversight of safety matters, particularly those that involve information
outside the level of the individual drug, sponsor, or DCB, as
described in Section E, below. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >FDA will devote more attention than it does
now to clarifying, updating, and making public the criteria for
NDA approval in all therapeutic areas and indications.  As new
therapies and indications arise and as the old ones evolve, FDA
will participate in public forums with sponsors and DCBs to establish
new criteria or modify existing ones.  The goal of this important,
ongoing interaction among FDA, sponsors, and DCBs is to establish
and publicize the objective criteria for approval, and also to
foster a cooperative interaction among the parties.  The existence
of up-to-date, objective criteria will promote consistency between
DCBs for similar products.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >During the evolution of the IND and NDA evaluation
and approval, FDA will not normally be exposed to the developing
project in any detail (except for major or unexpected Adverse
Drug Events (ADEs, see below)).  However, the agency will be kept
apprised of which drugs are being studied through periodic reports
from the DCBs.  These reports also will include information needed
to monitor safety information and allow general oversight, such
as: INDs issued (name of drug and sponsor); ADEs; and milestones
(dates and numbers of patients in the clinical development phases,
for instance).  During the IND phase, FDA will not routinely have
contact with the sponsor, but may at any time inspect or audit
the sponsor, DCB, or any other component of the drug-development
apparatus.  An FDA inspection might be triggered, for example,
by a suspected problem involving safety that has been inadequately
addressed, or information that raises concerns about the integrity
of data from an investigator or institution. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Once the NDA has been sent to FDA with the
DCB's recommendation for approval, the agency has a fixed period,
for example 90 days, to review the recommendation.  During this
90-day period, the Commissioner can approve the drug or reject
the NDA for a specified cause (which, in effect, rebuts the &quot;rebuttable
presumption&quot; of the DCB's recommendation). The 90-day period
of review is not extendable and the Commissioner's failure to
act during this period is deemed to be assent to the drug's approval.
 If the NDA is rejected, the DCB or the sponsor can appeal the
decision (a process which in turn must be completed in a further
90 days). The appeal mechanism is described below.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Clinical Drug Safety Oversight During the
IND</B></b>
<P>
<FONT >Safety oversight is largely unchanged in our
reform initiative.  We propose to keep intact the present national
system of pharmacovigilance administered by FDA, above the level
of the DCB. The current requirements and schedules for submitting
expedited and periodic safety reports will be maintained.  Under
the new system, reports will be submitted by the sponsor to the
DCB, which will transmit reportable ADEs to FDA.  FDA communications
(including any alerts based on safety data received by FDA from
U.S. or international sources) will be made to the DCB with a
copy to the sponsor.  In this way, the DCB will continue to have
primary oversight of the sponsor's handling of safety issues,
while FDA will maintain a broad purview.  In addition, FDA will
be able to obtain the safety data necessary for compliance with
international agreements on the reporting of safety data.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >To aid FDA's safety oversight, as already described,
the DCB will inform FDA periodically of the status of the INDs
it is overseeing.  The objective of these reports is primarily
to provide FDA with information necessary for its oversight of
the safety of human subjects -- not to allow the agency to create
an active or primary role for itself in the routine oversight
of clinical programs.  (A secondary objective is to permit FDA
to plan its review of DCB recommendations.)  It is expected that
most issues that arise in the course of drug development will
be resolved by sponsor-DCB interactions without involving FDA.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<b><FONT >Status of the Regulations Implementing the
Law</b></b>
<P>
<u>Safety and Effectiveness</u> 
<FONT >Currently, a drug's sponsor must demonstrate
its safety and effectiveness through controlled clinical tests
that are themselves closely regulated by FDA.  Before a new drug
can be marketed, FDA must determine that -- based on the data
submitted -- the drug is effective and reasonably safe for use
under the drug's labeling. It is important to note that Congress
did not create exact definitions of what is meant by &quot;effectiveness&quot;
or &quot;safety,&quot; and that the law does not supply such definitions.
 Rather, the law provides for these judgments to be made by <I>experts</I>
&quot;qualified by scientific training and experience.&quot; 
Nowhere is it specified that such experts should be exclusively
FDA employees, although that is how the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic
Act has come to be interpreted.  This interpretation is, in effect,
just a custom that the FDA has imposed and the industry has come
to accept, even though it was not the intent of Congress as expressed
in the law; in fact, this interpretation goes beyond the letter
of the statutes.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Our proposal for reform conforms more closely,
we believe, to the original intent of the existing statutes and
regulations governing safety and effectiveness.  Some proposed
changes, such as the identity and location of the &quot;experts&quot;
required by law, will prevent the statute from being distorted
or over-interpreted.  No change is proposed in the existing legal
standard for premarket approval, which requires evidence of safety
and substantial evidence of effectiveness derived from adequate
and well-controlled investigations as evaluated by experts qualified
by scientific training and experience.  The DCB experts' recommendation
that a drug should be approved will be, in legal terms, a rebuttable
presumption that the drug meets the law's safety and effectiveness
requirements.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U><FONT >The Regulations That Implement the Law<U><P>

<FONT >We believe that the current set of regulations
that implement FDA's enabling statutes, and the agency's interpretations
of them, are in many places unnecessarily complex and extend beyond
what the law -- and scientific principles -- require.  These can
and should be simplified, to be made more consistent with the
intent of the law.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In order to provide for an orderly transition
to the new system and to maintain consistency with internationally
harmonized formats, the current regulations will initially be
retained.  However, as experience is gained with the new system
during the transition period, a standing committee with representatives
from FDA, sponsors, and DCBs will revise and simplify the regulations
in order to streamline the IND/NDA process while keeping it consistent
with the requirements of the law.  Such revised regulations could
be converted to a status in which adherence to them by a sponsor
would be sufficient, but not necessary, to meet legal requirements.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >As discussed above, there must be ready access
to up-to-date standards of evidence needed for NDA approval. 
For the proposed system to work effectively, FDA, working cooperatively
with DCBs and sponsors, will continue to produce and update the
standards that apply.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >The Appeals Process</B><P></b>
<FONT >Two major problems have systematically prevented
industry from voicing complaints about the process or content
of FDA's decisions.  First, there has been no venue of independent
appeal for a party with a valid complaint; and second, there has
been a justified fear of agency reprisals.  Although there is
an FDA ombudsman, he currently reports to the Commissioner. Some
would look to the FDA advisory committees, but they are selected
and managed by FDA and address only issues presented to them by
FDA staff. There is no independent forum.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Our proposal creates an appeal mechanism for
DCB-FDA disagreements on product approval  -- an independent,
standing advisory committee of experts, the Committee on Medicines
Oversight, at the level of the office of the Secretary of the
Department of Health and Human Services (HHS).  It will have approximately
10-15 distinguished members representing patients, medical practice
and medical science, and the drug and device industries.  The
members of the committee will represent a wide spectrum of scientific,
medical, and regulatory expertise, and ad hoc members can be invited
as necessary.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The committee will hear appeals of FDA rejections
of a DCB recommendation, and will advise the Secretary, who will
instruct the Commissioner on the committee's decision.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Facilitating U.S. Approval of New Drugs
Approved Abroad</FONT></B></b>
<P>
<FONT >The efforts at international harmonization
of drug-approval standards and registration packages among advanced
countries implies that, in the future, other countries' evaluations
may not need to be completely duplicated in the United States.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >We propose to allow the direct submission to
FDA of an approved registration package from Europe (the European
Medicines Evaluation Agency (EMEA) or certain national regulatory
agencies, such as Great Britain's Medicines Control Agency). 
A foreign agency would function like a domestic DCB in that it
would submit summaries of the data on which its approval was based,
and the 90-day time period would apply for FDA to review and approve
or reject this package for the United States.  Alternatively,
the sponsor of a drug that had obtained (or was en route to) foreign
approval could contract with a U.S. DCB to review and submit its
NDA.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
